<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,1502,2034]" pageId="7" pageNumber="508">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1683,1709]" pageId="7" pageNumber="508">Description.</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[358,471,1683,1709]" captionStart="FIGURES 3–15" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1785,1809]" captionTargetBox="[181,1408,201,1744]" captionTargetId="figure-28@6.[177,1411,181,1761]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 3–15. Wing pattern. Figs 3–8: Hydria cervinalis cervinalis: Fig. 3, ♂, Germany, Sachsen-Anhalt, Mansfeld; Fig. 4, ♂, Ungarn, prov. Vesprérn, Zsofiapuszta; Fig. 5, ♂, Germany, Ug. Freyburg Zscheiplitz, Schafberg; Fig. 6, ♂, Germany, Umg. Jena; Figs 7 and 8, ♂, Germany, Sachsen-Anhalt, Mansfeld; Figs 9–10: H. cervinalis taurica ssp. n., Turkey, prov. Antalya, Civizli W Seydisehir, Fig. 9, Holotype ♂, (g. prep. DS-120/2012); Fig. 10, Paratype ♀, (g. prep. DS-121/2012); Figs 11–12: H. gernoti sp. n., Turkey, prov. Nigde, Ala Dagi: Fig. 11, Holotype ♂; Fig. 12, Paratype ♀; Figs 13–15: H. schachti sp. n.: Fig. 13, Holotype ♂, Turkey, prov. Erzurum, Meschit Daglari; Fig. 14, Paratype ♀, Turkey, prov. Erzurum, Meschit Daglari; Fig. 15, Paratype ♂, Turkey, prov. Erzurum, Karadeniz Daglari, Korga Dari. a = upperside; b = underside." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5896501" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5896501/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="508">Figs 9–10</figureCitation>
) Large subspecies with a wingspan in males 
<quantity box="[966,1088,1683,1710]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.8" metricValueMax="3.9" metricValueMin="3.7" pageId="7" pageNumber="508" unit="mm" value="38.0" valueMax="39.0" valueMin="37.0">37–39 mm</quantity>
, in females 
<quantity box="[1219,1341,1683,1710]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.85" metricValueMax="4.0" metricValueMin="3.7" pageId="7" pageNumber="508" unit="mm" value="38.5" valueMax="40.0" valueMin="37.0">37–40 mm</quantity>
. Ground colour of forewing on average somewhat lighter than in typical 
<taxonomicName authority="cervinalis" box="[865,1178,1719,1745]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Hydria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="508" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="cervinalis" subSpecies="cervinalis">
<emphasis box="[865,1178,1719,1745]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="508">Hydria cervinalis cervinalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Basal half of terminal area lightened, ochre-brown, well contrasting with the postmedian. Transverse lines faint or absent. Underside of the wings dull grey-brown. Discal spots and postmedian fascia distinct, dark grey. The postmedian running more or less straight towards costa. At vein R5 somewhat curved basally up to the costa, reaching the latter in an acute or right angle. Transverse lines indistinct or absent.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,1502,2034]" box="[199,807,1899,1926]" pageId="7" pageNumber="508">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,515,1899,1925]" pageId="7" pageNumber="508">Male and female genitalia.</emphasis>
See Diagnose part below.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="509" pageId="7" pageNumber="508" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,1502,2034]" lastBlockId="8.[151,1436,151,717]" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="509" pageId="7" pageNumber="508">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,322,1935,1961]" pageId="7" pageNumber="508">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Stadie &amp; Fiebig &amp; Rajaei, 2022" authorityName="Stadie &amp; Fiebig &amp; Rajaei" authorityYear="2022" box="[329,614,1935,1961]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Hydria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="508" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="cervinalis" status="ssp. n." subSpecies="taurica">
<emphasis box="[329,614,1935,1961]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="508">Hydria cervinalis taurica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[621,692,1936,1962]" pageId="7" pageNumber="508" rank="subSpecies">ssp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is very similar to the nominate subspecies in external appearance. However, on forewing upper side the terminal area is remarkably lightened towards postmedian fascia and transverse lines are more or less absent. On wing underside in the new subspecies the transverse lines, except the postmedian fascia, are nearly absent. The latter is running usually straighter than in the nominate subspecies. Male genitalia are very similar to the nominate subspecies, with shorter apical part of uncus and broader valva in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stadie &amp; Fiebig &amp; Rajaei" authorityYear="2022" box="[1267,1398,187,213]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Hydria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="509" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="cervinalis" subSpecies="taurica">
ssp. 
<emphasis box="[1317,1398,187,212]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="509">taurica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In addition, in the new subspecies juxta is less elongated, its median fork is more prominent (see 
<figureCitation box="[1188,1312,223,249]" captionStart="FIGURES 26–30" captionStartId="17.[151,264,1858,1882]" captionTargetBox="[215,1377,190,1821]" captionTargetId="figure-20@17.[207,1380,181,1834]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURES 26–30. Male genitalia. Fig. 26: Hydria cervinalis cervinalis (Germany, Kaiserstuhl, Badberg, g. prep. 2326/2020 H. Rajaei); Fig. 27: Hydria cervinalis taurica subsp. n., Paratype, (Turkey, prov. Antalya, Civizli W Seydisehir, g. prep. DS- 122/2012); Fig. 28: Hydria gernoti sp. n., Paratype, (Turkey, Nigde, Ala Dagi, g. prep. DS 99/2012); Fig. 29: Hydria schachti sp. n. Paratype (Turkey, Ispir, g. prep. DS-112/2012); Fig. 30, Hydria (cf.) sp. n., paratype (Azerbaijan, Talysh, Zuvand, g. prep. DS-05/2012); a = genitalia capsule; b = aedeagus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5896509" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5896509/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="509">Figs 26, 27</figureCitation>
) compared to the nominate subspecies. Female genitalia of new subspecies are similar to that of nominate subspecies, but the ductus bursae is narrower and slightly longer than in nominate subspecies (
<figureCitation box="[992,1122,295,321]" captionStart="FIGURES 40–47" captionStartId="20.[151,264,1791,1815]" captionTargetBox="[237,1345,194,1757]" captionTargetId="figure-28@20.[229,1359,181,1768]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURES 40–47. Female genitalia. Fig. 40: Hydria cervinalis cervinalis (Germany, Kaiserstuhl, Badberg, g. prep. 2327/2020 H. Rajaei); Fig. 41: Hydria cervinalis taurica subsp. n., Paratype, (Turkey, prov. Antalya, Civizli W Seydisehir, g. prep. DS- 121/2012); Fig. 42: Hydria gernoti sp. n., Paratype, (Turkey, prov. Nigde, Ala Dagi, g. prep. 2317/2020 H. Rajaei); Fig. 43: Hydria schachti sp. n. Paratype (Georgia, Achaltzych, g. prep. LL 38/2011); Fig. 44. Hydria gaudarica (Spain, Albarracin, g. prep. DS-107/2012); Fig. 45: Hydria hyrcana, syntype (Iran, Hajiabad, g. prep. 1555 H. Rajaei); Fig. 46: Hydria montivagata montivagata (Switzerland, Zermatt, g. prep. 2329/2020 H. Rajaei); Fig. 47, Hydria loebeli sp. n., Patatype (Turkey, prov. Nigde, Aladag, g. prep. DS-175/2012)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5896515" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5896515/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="509">Figs 40, 41</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1436,151,717]" pageId="8" pageNumber="509">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,309,330,356]" pageId="8" pageNumber="509">Genetics.</emphasis>
The single sequenced barcode of the new subspecies (GWOTL494-13) is clustered with 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Scopoli" baseAuthorityYear="1763" box="[1293,1436,331,357]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Hydria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="509" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cervinalis">
<emphasis box="[1293,1436,331,357]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="509">H. cervinalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[213,317,367,393]" name="Germany" pageId="8" pageNumber="509">Germany</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[371,422,367,393]" name="Italy" pageId="8" pageNumber="509">Italy</collectingCountry>
with 2.63% minimum genetic distance.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="509" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1436,151,717]" box="[199,869,402,429]" pageId="8" pageNumber="509">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,402,428]" pageId="8" pageNumber="509">Distribution.</emphasis>
Known only from the 
<typeStatus box="[608,656,403,429]" pageId="8" pageNumber="509">type</typeStatus>
locality in 
<collectingCountry box="[783,865,403,429]" name="Turkey" pageId="8" pageNumber="509">Turkey</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1436,151,717]" pageId="8" pageNumber="509">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,298,438,464]" pageId="8" pageNumber="509">Habitat.</emphasis>
The new subspecies inhabits sub-continental summer-green open deciduous forests dominated by 
<taxonomicName box="[151,320,475,501]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fagaceae" genus="Quercus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fagales" pageId="8" pageNumber="509" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="cerris">
<emphasis box="[151,320,475,501]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="509">Quercus cerris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
L., open forest and rocky slopes at the continental escarpments of the Middle Taurus Mountains between 
<quantity box="[251,420,511,537]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.35" metricValueMax="1.7" metricValueMin="1.0" pageId="8" pageNumber="509" unit="m" value="1350.0" valueMax="1700.0" valueMin="1000.0">
<geoCoordinate box="[251,314,511,537]" degrees="1,000" direction="north" orientation="latitude" pageId="8" pageNumber="509" precision="55" value="1.0">1,000</geoCoordinate>
<geoCoordinate box="[314,392,511,537]" degrees="1,700" direction="west" orientation="longitude" pageId="8" pageNumber="509" precision="55" value="-1.7">–1,700</geoCoordinate>
m
</quantity>
(
<figureCitation box="[436,520,511,537]" captionStart="FIGURES 71–77" captionStartId="23.[151,264,1728,1752]" captionTargetBox="[249,1339,183,1703]" captionTargetId="figure-20@23.[249,1339,181,1704]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURES 71–77. Photos of habitat and adult specimens. Fig. 71. Col Du Zad, province Khenifra, Morocco. The locality is a habitat of Hydria gudarica (DUFaY, 1983) at 2,135m. The habitat is an open Cedar forest mixed with dry, species-rich meadows (photo. noRbERT PöLL); Fig. 72. Turkey, Middle Taurus, Civizli, type locality of Hydria cervinalis taurica ssp. n. during the flight period of the adults in mid-May. The forests in the background are dominated by Quercus cerris and Juniperus excelsa. At forest clearings Berberis species and wild Pyrus trees are present (photo DIRK STaDIE); Fig. 73. Hydria gernoti sp.n. male PT, Turkey, Province Nigde, Als dagi, Sulucaova vic., 2,100m, ex ovo (photo DIRK STaDIE); Figs 74–75. Type locality of Hydria gernoti sp. n. in the Ala dagi mountains at 2,300m in mid-May. In foreground right some leafless bushes of Berberis (photo DIRK STaDIE, RaLF FIEbIG); Figs 76–77. Habitat of Hydria loebeli sp. n. and H. gernoti sp. n., small river valley near Göreme, Central Turkey (photo DIRK STaDIE, RaLF FIEbIG)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5896521" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5896521/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="509">Fig. 72</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1436,151,717]" box="[199,1074,547,574]" pageId="8" pageNumber="509">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,329,547,573]" pageId="8" pageNumber="509">Phenology.</emphasis>
Adults of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stadie &amp; Fiebig &amp; Rajaei" authorityYear="2022" box="[447,577,547,573]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Hydria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="509" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="cervinalis" subSpecies="taurica">
ssp. 
<emphasis box="[496,577,547,572]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="509">taurica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
wereobserved mid-May (very limited data).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="509" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1436,151,717]" pageId="8" pageNumber="509">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,295,582,608]" pageId="8" pageNumber="509">Biology.</emphasis>
Most probably the larvae of the new subspecies feed also on one of the Turkish 
<taxonomicName box="[1180,1363,583,609]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Berberidaceae" genus="Berberis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ranunculales" pageId="8" pageNumber="509" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[1180,1276,583,609]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="509">Berberis</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
(more investigation needed).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="509" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1436,151,717]" pageId="8" pageNumber="509">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,655,681]" pageId="8" pageNumber="509">Remarks.</emphasis>
It is to expect that the taxon merits species rank by zoogeographic reasons. The material is very scarce. Further investigation is needed to solve this question.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
